}
interface DeleteEvent<T> {
  type: 'delete'; ownerId: string; book: string; id: string; prev: T
}
```

`prev` is always populated for `update` and `delete` events. The pre-read cost is only paid when handlers are registered for the book.

input.new_string:
```typescript
type ChangeEvent<T extends BookEntry> =
  | CreateEvent<T>
  | UpdateEvent<T>
  | DeleteEvent<T>
  | BookDeleteEvent

interface CreateEvent<T> {
  type: 'create'; ownerId: string; book: string; entry: T
}
interface UpdateEvent<T> {
  type: 'update'; ownerId: string; book: string; entry: T; prev: T
}
interface DeleteEvent<T> {
  type: 'delete'; ownerId: string; book: string; id: string; prev: T
}
interface BookDeleteEvent {
  type: 'delete-book'; ownerId: string; book: string
}
```

`prev` is always populated for `update` and `delete` events. The pre-read cost is only paid when handlers are registered for the book.

**`BookDeleteEvent` carries no per-row payload.** A whole-book retirement is a single book-level event, not a fan-out of per-row deletes. The event is delivered Phase 2 only — `dropBook` is irreversible from the caller's perspective, so a Phase-1 handler cannot meaningfully roll it back. Watchers registered through `watch()` receive `'delete-book'` alongside row events; any handler that exhaustively switches on `event.type` must add a case for it (the TypeScript exhaustiveness check is the audit mechanism). After a `dropBook`, watchers for the dropped book remain in the registry but become dormant — no future writes can fire them.

